<span id="freeTextContainer18226738216153677195">While I read this book on a tear - that was mostly because I was on a trip with no other options. I hadn&apos;t realized that this wasn&apos;t completely written by Bradley, but it does show. I was interested in Margaret and how she would fit in on Darkover and how she would handle her late-awakening laran, but there were so many flaws. Her father Lew changed completely over the course of the book, with no explanation. Margaret said she was so close to Rafaella, her Renunciate guide, but that wasn&apos;t shown</span>
  <span id="freeText18226738216153677195" style="display:none">While I read this book on a tear - that was mostly because I was on a trip with no other options. I hadn't realized that this wasn't completely written by Bradley, but it does show. I was interested in Margaret and how she would fit in on Darkover and how she would handle her late-awakening laran, but there were so many flaws. Her father Lew changed completely over the course of the book, with no explanation. Margaret said she was so close to Rafaella, her Renunciate guide, but that wasn't shown much at all. Margaret's defeat of Ashara came too early in the novel - I didn't need 8 million pages about who would Margaret marry?!?!</span>
