  <span id="freeText296948299398640522" style="display:none">I recently read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/180270.Ammonite" title="Ammonite by Nicola Griffith" rel="nofollow noopener">Ammonite</a>, first published 1992, four years prior to this book, and I want to address the similarities in plot between that novel and this somewhere. I did love this book when I first read it as a teenager, but over the years I've become increasingly disillusioned about Darkover and MZB's work in general.<br /><br />Judge for yourself.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Margaret (Marguerida, Marja) Alton is a musicologist, sent to investigate the folk music of a mysterious, semi-recently rediscovered human colony. She has a poor relationship with her father and difficulty forming close relationships, though she is close to her mentor and his wife. On Darkover, she gradually discovers the mystical abilities of some inhabitants, falls ill with a local illness that usually hits those much younger than herself and nearly dies of fever. But in the aftermath of her illness, she discovers and slowly accepts new psychic abilities, learns to let others in, and finds love and family.<br /><br />Marghe (Marguerite) Taishan is an anthropologist, sent to investigate the cultures of a mysterious, recently rediscovered human colony. She has a poor relationship with her father, and difficulty forming close relationships, though some mention is made of a former lover. On Jeep, she gradually discovers the mystical abilities of some inhabitants, falls ill with a local illness that usually hits those much younger than herself and nearly dies of fever. But in the aftermath of her illness, she discovers and slowly accepts new psychic abilities, learns to let others in, and finds love and family.<br /><br />In both cases there is an outside force that wishes to exploit the resources of the planet, and characters spend a lot of time dealing with the cold.<br /><br />I can't be the first person to make this connection. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
